86. tribus lectis: cf. 2. 8. 20 n. quaternos: four on each conch, twelve in all. The usual number was nine. The fourth side of the table was open for the slaves to approach. 87. unus, ‘one of the guests! Some MSS. have imus=the guest occupying the last seat on the lectus imus ς cf. 2. 8. 20 n. The host often invited, for the amusement of himself and the rest of the company, scurrae, men whose wits were sharpened by their appetites‚ who were expected to say smart things in return for their dinner. These poor wits (quibus sunl verba sine penu el pecunia, Plaut. Capt. 3. 1. 12) had scats on the third or imus lectus. Cf.
